---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="About — Ethan Justice"
  path="/about/"
  description="Ethan Justice — cloud security analyst. What I think about building systems that fail safely, and the projects where I proved it."
>
  <div class="wrap prose">
    <h1>About</h1>

    <p class="lede">
      I'm a cloud security analyst. I govern cloud environments for a Fortune
      500 insurer by day, and run my own infrastructure like production by
      night.
    </p>
    <p>
      The through-line, if there is one: the interesting part of security is
      never the exploit. It's whether the thing was built so the exploit had
      somewhere to go. That's a design question, and it gets decided long before
      anyone attacks you.
    </p>

    <h2>What I actually think</h2>
    <p>
      Anyone can assert these. So each one links to the place on this site where
      you can watch it hold.
    </p>

    <ol class="positions">
      <li>
        <p class="pos-claim">
          The guard has to be architectural, not textual.
        </p>
        <p class="pos-where">
          "Don't reveal X" in a prompt fails the first time someone is clever or
          insistent. The only defense that holds is an agent that doesn't
          possess the thing. Send it an injection and watch it have nothing to
          give up. <a href="/projects/jarvis/">try to break it →</a>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p class="pos-claim">
          A backup that has never been restored is a hope, not a backup.
        </p>
        <p class="pos-where">
          Same for isolation. Kill the tunnel and the workloads lose the
          internet rather than quietly falling back to the LAN, because the
          fallback route doesn't exist.
          <a href="/projects/homelab/#trace=bypass">watch it fail closed →</a>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p class="pos-claim">
          Prevention beats detection, and it isn't close.
        </p>
        <p class="pos-where">
          A control that evaluates at creation has no exposure window to
          measure. Detection's best case still costs you the lag plus however
          long a human takes.
          <a href="/projects/cloud-security/">run the timeline →</a>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p class="pos-claim">
          Measure before you optimise, or you'll spend the night on the wrong
          thing.
        </p>
        <p class="pos-where">
          I instrumented my voice assistant expecting text-to-speech to be the
          bottleneck. It was the fastest stage in the pipeline.
          <a href="/projects/jarvis/">build the pipeline →</a>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p class="pos-claim">
          Run what you build.
        </p>
        <p class="pos-where">
          I ship my own images of the recipe app my household actually eats
          from, so every regression I write lands on the machine I use at
          dinner. It's the fastest feedback loop I have.
          <a href="/projects/mealie/">see the bug →</a>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p class="pos-claim">
          Own the code, and "I wish it had X" becomes a thing you just do.
        </p>
        <p class="pos-where">
          Eleven releases of a manga reader later, that has been true every
          time. <a href="/projects/makimono/">drive the reader →</a>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

